tags":["lawyer","ohio_migration"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"death","header":"Died at thirty-nine; wife outlived him fifty years","body":"Edward left West Hampton MA as a Williams College graduate, practiced law in Ohio and Massachusetts, then pivoted to soda manufacturing in Cleveland — dying there August 1, 1841 at only thirty-nine, leaving two children under age seven. His wife Mary Ann Dwight survived him until June 4, 1891, outliving him by exactly fifty years."},{"number":2,"category":"character","header":"Became, late in life, a man of prayer","body":"The obituary that marked Edward's death at thirty-nine focused less on his law practice at D.H. Lamb & Co. than on the man he had become: late in life he united with the Congregational Church in Ohio City and was remembered by those who knew him simply as 'a man of prayer.' For a direct descendant of Rev. Thomas Hooker — who helped establish the Congregational tradition in Connecticut two centuries earlier — the phrase carried the full weight of inheritance."},{"number":3,"category":"career","header":"Williams 1820; youngest son of a man who","body":"Edward Hooker graduated Williams College in 1820 and practiced law at Ravenna Ohio, then South Hadley Massachusetts, before settling in Cleveland with D.H. Lamb & Co. He was the youngest son of Dr. William Hooker of Westhampton, who lived to ninety-four — Edward died at thirty-nine."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"edward-hooker-1802"},"I01162":{"id":"I01162","is_placeholder":false,"former_ids":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Mary Ann Dwight Hooker","first_name":"Mary Ann","last_name":"Hooker","maiden_name":"Dwight","married_names":["Hooker"]},"gender":"female","birth":{"year":1810,"month":9,"day":12,"city":"South Hadley","county":"Hampshire","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1891,"month":6,"day":4,"city":"South Hadley","county":"Hampshire","